# Color in Three.js

Colors can be set several ways:

```
// Hex literal (most common)
mesh.material.color.setHex(0x4466ff);

// From CSS string
const c = new THREE.Color('hsl(220, 70%, 55%)');

// RGB components 0..1
const c = new THREE.Color(0.27, 0.4, 1.0);

// In material constructor
new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x4466ff })
```

Three.js Color stores values as linear RGB (0..1 per channel). When you pass a hex value it automatically converts from sRGB gamma space to linear.

# HSL Color Space

HSL (Hue, Saturation, Lightness) is often more intuitive than RGB for generating color palettes:

```
const c = new THREE.Color();

// setHSL(h, s, l) — all values 0..1
c.setHSL(0.6, 0.7, 0.55);  // blue
c.setHSL(0.0, 0.7, 0.55);  // red
c.setHSL(0.3, 0.7, 0.55);  // green
```

Generate a color wheel by sweeping hue:

```
for (let i = 0; i < N; i++) {
  const h = i / N;          // 0..1
  c.setHSL(h, 0.7, 0.55);
  meshes[i].material.color.copy(c);
}
```

For palettes, fix S and L and vary H. For mood shifts, vary S or L while keeping H constant.

# Physically-Based Rendering

MeshStandardMaterial has two key PBR parameters:

```
new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({
  roughness: 0.0,  // 0 = mirror-smooth, 1 = fully matte
  metalness: 0.0,  // 0 = dielectric, 1 = conductor
})
```

## The Four Archetypes

```
// Rough dielectric — chalk, concrete, matte paint
{ roughness: 0.9, metalness: 0.0 }

// Rough conductor — brushed steel, cast iron
{ roughness: 0.9, metalness: 1.0 }

// Smooth dielectric — polished plastic, lacquer
{ roughness: 0.05, metalness: 0.0 }

// Smooth conductor — chrome, mirror-polished metal
{ roughness: 0.05, metalness: 1.0 }
```

In between gives you every material in between — anodized aluminium, satin finish, worn metal, etc.

# Emissive Materials

Emissive color makes a surface appear to glow — it adds light to the final pixel regardless of scene lighting.

```
new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({
  color:              0x224499,
  emissive:           0x0011ff,
  emissiveIntensity:  0.6,
})
```

Emissive does not actually emit light into the scene (use a PointLight for that). It only affects the surface's own color.

Animate emissiveIntensity in update() for pulsing or power indicators:

```
export function update(ctx, dt) {
  const pulse = 0.4 + 0.6 * Math.sin(ctx.elapsed * 3);
  mesh.material.emissiveIntensity = pulse;
}
```

# Environment Maps

For the most realistic look, smooth metals and plastics need an environment map — an HDR panorama that provides realistic reflections.

```
import { RGBELoader } from
  'three/addons/loaders/RGBELoader.js';

const loader = new RGBELoader();
const texture = await loader.loadAsync('/env/studio.hdr');
texture.mapping = THREE.EquirectangularReflectionMapping;
ctx.scene.environment = texture;
```

Once set on `scene.environment`, all MeshStandardMaterial objects automatically pick up the environment for reflections and IBL (image-based lighting).

Combined with low roughness and metalness = 1.0, this produces mirror-quality chrome reflections.
